Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to study social work to help children who are abused or neglected. I also want to support families with problems. My values for social work are service, respect, and ethical behavior. I want to help improve relationships between people and learn more about my job to stay good at it.

I have always wanted to help others but did not know what career to choose. In high school and college, I saw people avoid problems and use bad coping methods. I saw this and decided to study psychology. I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009 and took a break. One day I visited a friend and met a sixteen-year-old boy. He was scared because his parents were abusive. He called the police. I went to his house and talked to the police. They asked me to talk to his parents. I did, and they said the boy was “manipulative.” I thought about becoming a social worker after this.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says individuals are important but wants us to be the same. I am different and protest against unfairness. I color my hair, wear different clothes, and fight against racism and discrimination. I will always stand against social injustice.

This paper talks about two models: Biological and Sociocultural. These models explain the disorder insomnia.

Biological model:
- Focuses on genes and health.
- Neurons in the brain control sleep and wakefulness.
- Study with mice shows that a receptor (GABAB) helps sleep. If it does not work well, people may have trouble sleeping. This could be due to genetics.

Sociocultural model:
- Looks at how the environment affects sleep.
- Factors include race, ethnicity, and social status.

The study looks at these models and explains research on insomnia. It also talks about the good and bad parts of each study.

Sleep disorders are:
- Primary: Trouble staying asleep or awake.
- Related to another disorder: Sleep problems from mental disorders.
- Other: From health issues or drugs.

Primary insomnia is trouble staying asleep. Primary hypersomnia is trouble staying awake. Narcolepsy is a sleep disorder with cataplexy or automatic REM sleep. Dyssomnias are sleep problems with starting and staying asleep. Parasomnias are sleep problems with behaviors or physical events.

The review looks at insomnia and some primary sleep disorders. It focuses on the biological and sociocultural models.

This paper talks about three things: what Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) is, how to find it, and how to help students with CAPD in a classroom.

CAPD is when the brain has trouble using sound information. People with CAPD can hear normally but their brain does not process sounds correctly. This is different from hearing problems. In the 1950s, people started to notice this in children with communication problems.

CAPD can cause problems like not hearing sounds from different places, having trouble with sounds, not hearing sound patterns, and not understanding changes in speech. It also can cause sounds to be blocked or not understood in sequence.

To find CAPD, a person should be tested by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, or psychologists. Tests can include looking at how a person responds to sounds and asking them to do tasks with sounds. There is no one test that works all the time. No one knows the cause of CAPD.

Teachers can help students with CAPD in a few ways. They can repeat important information, use clear speech, and give extra time for tasks. They can also sit close to the student and use visual aids for help.

Twelfth Night talks about how hiding one's true self can be good for tricks, but it can also cause problems. People might feel alone when they stop hiding. They must decide between saving themselves or keeping their relationships. Some people might not like being tricked. The story of Viola is special. She hides as a man to protect herself in a new country. She becomes popular, but it also separates her from women. Olivia thinks she loves Cesario, but she might really love women. Olivia switches her love to Sebastian quickly. She might not love Cesario/Viola as a lover, but as a family member.

German rule in Africa was known for its cruelty, especially in South West Africa where many people were killed. This was only one part of the German empire, though. The empire had many different places and ways of ruling. Education was also different in each colony. In East Africa, the British found many educated Africans after taking over in 1919. In other places, like Cameroon, people also liked the German education. South West Africa was different. The government did not help much with native education. Missionaries did, but they had little support. The government did help Europeans, giving them schools. This had long effects on South West Africa. Most people there were still uneducated when the Germans left. Many reasons caused this difference. This paper will explain these reasons, especially new research about what settlers and authorities thought of native Africans. There is much reading about German education in Africa. Most is in German and from the early 1900s. It described the schools in each colony. Other books compared schools in different colonies. Cohen's book talked about South West Africa and East Africa. He said the many settlers in South West Africa made its education system different. South West Africa had a mild climate, so many Europeans lived there. By 1913, there were nearly 15,000 whites, while 5,336 lived in the next largest colony, East Africa.

]People have made many kinds of popular music. Heavy metal is one kind. It started 40 years ago. It is very different and has many parts. It has many kinds of emotions. Most of these emotions are dark. People can make many kinds of heavy metal. They start with one kind, then make a new kind, and then another new kind. Today, there are many kinds of heavy metal. People do not know what heavy metal is. They say it is a movement. A movement is like a group of people who like the same thing. Heavy metal is a music of more. It is heavier, louder, and more violent. People in heavy metal bands play their instruments very well. They use drugs to make their music. People make heavy metal in many ways. Henri Rousseau painted his dreams before surreal art began. He started this when he was an adult. He wanted people to like his art. His painting called "The Dream" shows a woman dreaming. It also shows his dreams and goals. Rousseau struggled with whether to paint like other artists or be different. Before understanding "The Dream," learn about Rousseau's life. He was born in 1844 in France. He worked at tolls. His wife and children died. He started painting to feel better. Unlike other artists, he was not highly educated. He was older when he started painting. Other artists like Matisse got famous while he was still trying. Matisse and Rousseau had different goals: Matisse wanted to avoid boring art, Rousseau wanted to make good art to be accepted by the art world.

Many smart people think ethics and beauty are connected. I believe this is true. John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn many things in life through education or experience. But we like ethics and beauty without being taught. Both ethics and beauty help us understand things, not make rules. We try to explain why something is good or beautiful, not just judge.

Critics can't always explain what makes something good or beautiful. For example, people talk about the Mona Lisa's colors and history. But they can't say why it's good art. People often say, "There's just something about it" before explaining. I think art and morality have a special quality that we can't fully explain. As Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." Ethics and art both can't be fully explained. This special quality is what makes them powerful and connected.

We feel ethics and art deeply. This is like Kant's noumenal experience—something we feel but can't fully explain. Literature is special because it has strong moral value. It helps us understand life's values.

Germany is strong. People love German culture. It comes from München in the Alps to Kiel near the Baltic Sea. It is also felt in Köln by the Rhine River and in Dresden on the Elbe River. German culture is a mix of many things.

Germany comes from many places. Some people think the name comes from a group called the Tungrians. Others think it comes from a spear. Some say it comes from the Old Irish word for loud. Germany's story is old.

The Romans wrote about Germany. They called it Germania. They said Germans lived there since long ago. They lived near the Roman Empire's edge. They traded and worked in Roman army. (REWRITE)/

I looked at the bowl. I did not understand it well. My mind was empty. I looked at it without feeling. I saw it like an artist. I tried to study it. I thought about it, but my thoughts went away quickly. I did not have my own thoughts. I just felt what I saw.

I had a book. It taught me about drawing. A teacher said it was good. It taught me about pencils and how our brain sees lines. It said to put a square frame around what you want to draw. This made pictures easier to see.

I looked at a bowl. I could not put the square frame around it. I was too surprised. I was like an artist. I wanted to start my own story. I wanted to draw it.

I held my pencil. I drew. I made water. I made flakes. I made a story. I wanted to move the brown package. I flushed the toilet. It did not move. I tried again. It still did not move.

I held a mop. I tied my tie. I looked at the brown package. I was not happy. I looked at the wall. I wrapped the toilet paper around my hand. I dipped it into the water. I was like a mother cooking Thanksgiving turkey.

Teens are dying in car accidents. Several problems cause this. The teen brain is not ready for driving. They are also inexperienced. This causes more accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens do worse when they drive with friends. A study showed this. California and other states try to make teen driving safer. They limit driving hours and prohibit other teens as passengers. But these are only small fixes.
The main problem is that teens are not ready to drive safely. Even 18 is too young, says psychologist Marvin Zuckerman. Teens under 19-20 like to take risks. So, delaying driving until this changes could help. If we don't, accidents will happen more and the death toll will rise. By 2010, more teens will be able to drive.
Schools can teach teens to drive. But no one under 18 can drive alone. A permit can be given before a full license. Certain driving hours are needed. This can be based on what many states already require. This will help teens all across the country. This idea is not new.

I looked at many early Edison films in the Library of Congress. I watched all 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make tricks. I studied the poetry of these films and looked at how they changed over time. Most trick films are set-bound and use a frontal proscenium. They have no camera movement. They use long and medium shots. Most follow the rule of one shot = one film. But some films at the start of the 20th century break these rules. They use multiple shots.

One common feature of trick films is their use of an interior set within a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move. This is like old theatre and vaudeville. Characters in these films mostly move side-to-side. They never walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth. They do not walk towards or away from the camera.

Trick films usually have long shots and sometimes medium shots. They never use close-ups. This is like old theatre and vaudeville. Audience sees the whole performance at once. Actors do not move towards the camera, so no close-ups are made.

Most early trick films have one shot = one film. This limits film length to about a minute or less. It also limits the story or drama. Most trick films show short vaudeville tricks. But in trick films, a single shot might have many joined parts. Look at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). It looks like one shot, but it has many parts joined together.

John Taylor from Caroline was a early and strong believer in Republican ideas. He was mainly a farmer, but his short time in politics made him known for his strong beliefs about freedom and the government. His love of farming helped him form his ideas about the government.

Taylor thought the United States had a chance to create a perfect system because there were no strong traditions to stop them. He believed in natural rights. These rights are all important and connected. If one right is taken away, all others suffer. So, these rights should not be controlled by the government.

Taylor wanted a government that understands good and bad in people. He believed that people have both good and bad in them. He thought good principles should protect private property, help farming, and fight capitalism. A government with good principles would be fair, even if the leaders are greedy.

Taylor wanted a government with few powers. He thought a small government would not be expensive or evil. But he also thought a simple, literal interpretation of the Constitution could be bad. He thought the Declaration of Independence was the true guide for the United States because it talked about a group of states, not one nation.

In the project, commuter log submissions fell sharply in the third month. We did not know the reason. Winter and end of the semester may have caused this. People do not commute by bicycle or foot. Many students and faculty stay home due to holidays and semester breaks. February had low log submissions. The project started with much energy, but this faded. To fix this, we created the Carpool Challenge Week in March. This helped increase log submissions. A big challenge was to keep people interested. People like driving cars. We gave away gift certificates for food, books, massage, and more. We also thought giving away a nice bike, car, or electric car may help. The prizes did not change during the project. If we increased prize value, more people might have participated.

An ETF is a kind of security that follows an index, a commodity, or many assets like an index fund, but it trades like a stock. An ETF gives you the benefits of an index fund but with more flexibility. You can sell short, use margin, and buy one share. These benefits are good, but ETFs have less cost than mutual funds. However, you must pay a commission when you trade ETFs, like with stocks. ETFs have many types to choose from. It's important to check if the benefits, like diversification, really exist.

We are looking at an ETF called IHF and its top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To see if these 10 stocks represent the ETF well, we can calculate their Beta and return. The chart below shows these calculations.

The chart shows that the return of a portfolio with only the top 10 stocks is 6.11% higher than the ETF. The Beta of these stocks is also lower. This suggests that a portfolio of just the top 10 stocks could have higher returns and lower risk.

To check if these portfolios are really different, we need to compare their standard deviation. This will tell us if there's a real difference in risk.

Poe's "Dream-Land" uses the word "Thulé." This word is from Virgil's work. Poe knew German writers. Some people think Poe copied this from Goethe's poem, "The King of Thulé."
"Dream-Land" and "The King of Thulé" are similar. Both have a man who loses his wife and drinks too much. Both poems are about sadness and loneliness. Poe's "The Pit and the Pendulum" also uses "Thulé." It is like a companion piece to "Dream-Land." In "Dream-Land," the speaker says he is lonely and sees a dark, colorless world. This is like the scene in "The King of Thulé."
Goethe was important to Poe. He knew Goethe's work because it was popular in many places.

In California, if a store customer slips and falls on something like applesauce on the floor, the store could be punished for not cleaning it quickly. The customer might be able to show the store manager acted with bad intent. This is called "punitive damages." The manager knew about the spill twice and did nothing about it. This is because he was eating dinner. The customer could say the manager did something very bad.

A judge is unlikely to dismiss the customer's claim. The customer must show the manager acted with bad intent and knew it could cause harm. The customer could also say the manager should have known because other customers slipped and fell before. The manager did not do anything to fix the problem.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, a D&D Market employee told the manager about the applesauce spill. The manager said he was eating dinner and could not deal with it. Another employee told him again at 5:15 pm. At 5:30 pm, a customer, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell. She was hurt badly. Before this, five other customers slipped and fell in 2009.

In California, a customer can get punitive damages if a store acts with bad intent, fraud, or malice. This means the manager wanted to cause harm or knew it could happen and did not care. The manager was aware of the spill and did nothing to fix it. A court might say this is bad because the manager did not care about the customer's safety.

The ideas Jesus taught and his beliefs during his life were left behind when Christianity started after his death. In history, Christianity moved away from its start. San Diego County has a mild, sunny climate. So, it grows many things: tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people like organic food. So, there is a big market for it. Organic eggs and milk are also popular. Many organic farms offer tours and activities like hiking and birdwatching.

Organic farming has some benefits. It has more plants and animals in the area. It also does not use chemicals. But, it costs more. It needs more work to keep pests and weeds away and to grow things without chemicals. Small organic farms are less efficient than big ones. They also need more work to help wildlife, like planting cover crops and removing invasive species. So, the landowner might want help to make more money and improve nature.

The farm is next to Potrero town in unincorporated San Diego County. It is 160 acres with many types of plants and animals. The area was home to Native Americans and later used for grazing and wood. The land is part of a conservation plan. It protects many species, some of which are rare or endangered.

I found this land on a real estate website. I also looked at government programs to help small farmers. I studied an organic farm in the same area to learn what farming there might be like.

Culture is important in any negotiation. It can be hard to understand because it is not one thing. It is not the same for everyone. It also does not fit into simple statements like "all Japanese are polite." To be a good negotiator, you need to understand how a culture affects the talk. When you meet a new culture, you compare it to your own. To understand a new culture, you may study its history or learn about its beliefs. Do not judge a culture. Accept it and work within its rules, especially if you are not in a strong position. If you are on the other person's territory, respect their traditions and beliefs. This can help you overcome any cultural barriers and make the negotiation better.

Culture is not just about a country. Companies also have their own cultures. A company's culture can affect how people work and communicate. Some companies have rules about charity, others do not. Even in the same country, companies can have different cultures. For example, some American companies have strict dress codes, while others are more relaxed. Some cultures are not as diverse as American culture. They may seem simple from the outside, but they are more complex. Values are also important. They explain why people do things. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not say bad things about their company or boss. If a culture values hard work, a negotiator will not settle too quickly. Learn about your opponent's personal values to make the negotiation better.

The Bible says, "The fool says, 'There is no God.'" This is found in Psalm 14. St. Anselm and Thomas Aquinas both believe in this God. Their arguments are about this God.

To compare their arguments, we start with the idea that they are both correct. This is because their arguments are about the same thing. However, neither of them gives a full proof for God.

St. Anselm's argument is about finding God in our minds. He says that we can't think of God's nonexistence. This means that God is true because we know it in our minds. This is called faith.

Thomas Aquinas is different. He believes God can be proven by reason and evidence. He has five arguments to prove God exists. His arguments say that God is needed for things to change, cause things, be contingent, have degrees of excellence, and for harmony. He shows that God is needed for these things to exist.

In around 2500 years ago, a man who we call Buddha was born. He left the world and became enlightened. His teachings started Buddhism. Today, the most common form is called Theravada Buddhism. It has changed a lot over time. In Sri Lanka, a Theravada country, people have a yearly water-cutting ceremony. Monks and laypeople take part. Buddha did not teach about this. Theravada Buddhism has changed much. This change is due to forces inside and outside the religion.

There are some special words in this talk. Inside forces are from people in the religion, no matter if they are monks or not. Outside forces are from people not in the religion. Hostile forces want to harm the religion. Benign forces do not mean to harm or help. They may do so by mistake.

First, we will talk about the basics of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists take refuge in three things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the Tripitaka, which is three parts of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka has the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka has rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka has Buddhist thoughts. Anatta means no soul. Dukkha is inherent suffering. Anicca is change. Understanding these helps to stop Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. When we stop Sansara, lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion) also stop. Monks and laypeople follow rules in the Vinaya Pitaka. For laypeople, there are five rules: no killing, no lying, no stealing, no bad behavior, and no drugs. Monks follow many more rules. The four noble truths are important to Buddhism. The first truth is Dukkha, life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can end.

The United States and Mexico had a long, strong rivalry for many years, from 1836 to 1893. The most important part of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. In this war, the United States won and got Texas and the American Southwest as new land. Many other fights also happened between the two countries. The rivalry started because Americans and Mexicans had different beliefs, traditions, and interests. This is like many other rivalries between countries that share a border. The United States and Mexico are not like many other countries in Latin America, which have good relations with the United States. Religion was a big problem. Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy, like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. The rivalry had 17 disputes, mostly about borders and border raids. The rivalry ended when Mexico became dependent on the United States and American interests changed from taking more land to helping Mexico's economy.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly disabled by a sickness I did not know. I was a nurse. I chose this job because it was safe and secure. I heard this often when I was young: "You will always find work. People always get sick." So, I chose nursing even though I dreamed of being a scientist or journalist.

However, after 15 years, I am still disabled. I cannot work. I live on Social Security Disability. I have no money. Every day, I struggle to survive. I live in fear and low self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain.

I could not survive without help from my family and friends. When disaster happens, we need each other.

In life, there are always emergencies. We cannot prepare for everything. Some things are too big to face alone.

We should not trust only big government. Instead, we should trust each other. We should help each other and ask for help when needed. This is better than each person trying to solve problems alone.

Conservatives talk about rugged individualism, but our founding fathers did not succeed alone. They needed compassion and mutual respect.

So, be prepared. I have a disaster kit and supplies. I also know my neighbors. It is important to be prepared, but it is also important to trust and help each other.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules or limits that guide their changes? D'Arcy Thompson said in 1917 that scientists could not even describe simple shapes with math. Today, math helps study how mollusks grow and change. Our work uses math to understand how Prunum, a type of mollusk, grows and changes. We use X-ray pictures of Prunum shells to find numbers that help in math modeling. We also use experiments to study the growth. We model different shell shapes to see how they could change. These results help understand how Prunum changes over time.

A shell is like a tube that goes around in a circle. This circle is called a whorl. The center of the shell is called the columella. The shell grows with different sizes of whorls. The largest whorl is at the end, called the body whorl. The part before the last whorl is called the spire. The top of the spire is the apex and the bottom is the base. The animal lives in the shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different sides. The usual way is to see the aperture facing up. A method to count whorls is to draw a line from the first suture and count the whorls from there.

A shell can be seen as a series of openings that change over time and space. We can trace these openings using math. Once we know the math, we can change the shell's shape and size. This helps us understand how mollusks grow and change.

For 10 years, Indonesia's neonatal and infant death rates did not change much. Indonesia is close to the water and sanitation goals, but not the child and mother health goals for 2015. Many reasons explain this. We must improve the health system, not just specific programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers, but traditional workers like midwives cannot help with complicated pregnancies. This is why many mothers die from bleeding. Also, fewer children under five get treated for diarrhea by health professionals. Postnatal care is a worry too, with low rates across the country.

Cesarian-section rates are low, around 4%. They are even lower in rural areas, 2%. This shows that healthcare is not available in all areas. There is also a big difference in service use between the poor and rich, 27%. The poor find it hard to get healthcare because of costs.

The next step is to decide how to improve neonatal and maternal care. Should Indonesia focus on specific programs or improve the overall health system? Both options have pros and cons. Specific programs can target and solve problems quickly, but they can also take money away from other areas and cause duplication.

Victorian novels focus much on detail and the rich people of the time. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, do not fit this style. They have mystery and strange events, which help their characters. Oliver Twist has many dream-like scenes. These scenes show Oliver's thoughts and fears. He dreams of a shooting and being carried away. He cannot control the event. His health is bad. He feels fear and pain. He wonders who causes his problems. He feels defeated. He cannot save himself. He struggles to get help. He cannot even try to control the shooting. He feels defeated. He dreams about a long night and a short day. No night or day is real. He feels this way for a long time.

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program. I helped students in many subjects. My best subjects were English and reading. One boy, Adrian, needed help. He struggled with reading. He could say some letters, but others were hard. He spoke English well, but he didn't know the alphabet. I learned this when I met his mother. She spoke only Spanish. I didn't know Spanish well, but we talked. I found out Adrian could read, but he didn't know the alphabet. Maybe this helped him later.

I tell this story to show the language problem in schools. Even children who speak English well can have reading problems. This is a big problem. What can we do? In Adrian's case, tutoring helped. But for children who don't speak English, it's harder. There's no one answer. We need to combine many things.

First, two-way bilingual education is good. It helps all children. Some people think it's a waste. But it's not. If we use it more, all children will benefit. How can we do this? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. We can have bilingual helpers.

When we are young, we learn that there is something bigger than us. Some people go to church or temple to learn about it. Others search inside themselves. Many people follow the beliefs of their parents. But some people do not believe in anything bigger than themselves. They change their beliefs over time. We all try to find our own place in the world. We search for light in the darkness. We want to live good lives.

My father said his favorite bird was a cardinal. We sat on our porch one day, listening to the rain. My father looked at the rain, thinking. He was thin and weak. I felt alone and scared. I hugged him but did not talk about how much I would miss him. I did not watch him die. I remembered him by how he lived. I was in bed for three days, waiting for news. No one called me.

The Gothic novel is an old-new thing. It is both old in style and new in story. This is like a story with old parts and new parts. People like and dislike the Gothic novel. Some think it is not deep. Some think it is like the "terrible sublime" from Burke's writing.

The first Gothic novel is "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole. It uses old and new ideas. It uses old theater ideas and new nature ideas to make a new kind of story. It has old Gothic theater, architecture, and traditions.

People called Gothic many things. It is old in the past. It is not good in the modern world.

The Gothic novel stays for a long time. It is old and new. The reader can see the past and feel like it is new.

One idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. It is the old idea of a knight's training. It is used to show the perfect knight. It is romanticized and used to compare the past to the present.

Walpole wrote "The Castle of Otranto" during a troubled time. He was unhappy about the future. He thought the good qualities of people in the Gothic past were lost. He shows this in his writing, like with the character Frederic. Frederic has many chivalric traits. He is a prince and has suffered tragedy. He is like a gallant knight, but it is exaggerated, which is a Gothic trait.

Supply chain management is the process of moving products from customer order to delivery. It includes planning, making, and controlling the process. Keith Oliver, a consultant, invented this term in 1982. The supply chain includes six key parts: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the supply chain. Production decides when, why, where, and how to make products. Managers need to know what customers want. They can look at the market to understand customer demand.

Once managers know what customers want, they decide what products to make and how many. They also decide where to make these products. After deciding this, managers focus on planning workloads and maintaining equipment. Production is very important. Every detail matters.

The second key part is supply. Supply is about making strategic decisions for a facility and outsourcing partners. A company may have many divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager decides which division is best for each process. The manager may also outsource work to other companies to make products faster and cheaper.

Duke Ellington made many important contributions to jazz. He stayed in jazz for a long time, which helped him become a great composer. He wrote songs that showed the skills of his band members. He let soloists play freely and created songs that fit the band’s sound.

Ellington used the voice as a jazz instrument early in his career. This is shown in "Creole Love Call." In this song, the voice talks back and forth with the reeds. The voice starts smooth and then changes to a rough sound. The song uses call and response, where one section answers the other. Ellington’s band also plays in a special way to make the song sound good.

Ellington’s use of voice in "Creole Love Call" is just one example of how he added special sounds to his music. In "Hot and Bothered," he combined careful organization with good sound choices. The song uses a call and response between a muted trumpet and scat singing. In "It Don’t Mean a Thing," Ellington uses a trombone to introduce the melody. These songs show how Ellington used his band’s sounds to make his music great.

She always felt like something was missing. This feeling started when she was 14. It was still there at 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. No boys interested her. She tried to find out why. She thought about it for years. She had a peaceful life. Her parents were calm. They argued with her about independence. She was likeable because she was nice and fun. Today was not good. She heard a scream in the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground. She was in pain. "Take me to the hospital," her mother said. She drove her mother to the hospital. She asked for help. Doctors looked at her mother. She fell from a stool trying to get a vase.

A study showed that a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) is good for heart health. A new version of this diet, the "alternate Mediterranean Diet" (aMed), has more plant foods, less animal products, and some fish. It also has monounsaturated fats instead of saturated fats. A little alcohol is allowed.

Before, other studies showed that this diet helps prevent total and cardiovascular (CVD) deaths. It is also good for losing weight and lowering cholesterol. But, no studies looked at stroke or stroke deaths.

This study followed 74,886 women for 20 years. They were part of the "Nurses' Health Study." Six times, they reported what they ate. Most women stayed in the study.

The study used a score to measure how well they followed the aMed diet. It looked at heart disease, stroke, and stroke deaths. It also looked at many other things like weight, smoking, and exercise.

The study found that women who followed the diet well had less heart disease and stroke. Women who followed it best had 29% less heart disease and 25% less stroke than those who followed it least.

In 2007, the United States had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, the housing market fell, and big important companies were in trouble. This problem continues today. We must ask: how did this happen, and how can we stop it?

The crisis happened because banks and companies made bad choices. They gave loans to people who could not pay them back. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac made bad decisions too. They agreed to pay for these loans and sold them in packages. When people could not pay, the banks did not have enough money. They passed the problem on to others in the economy.

This began in 1999 during the Clinton administration. The president wanted to stay in power. He made it easier for people to get loans. This made the problem worse. Steven Holmes of the New York Times warned about this.

Many things combined to make the economy worse. New kinds of mortgages were used. These made the economy more connected to the housing market. This made the economy very sensitive to small changes in prices.

The housing bubble burst. The banks that bought mortgage packages lost a lot of money. Big investment banks like Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch had to sell themselves, or be taken over. Fannie and Freddie had a lot of mortgage debt and were put under government control in 2008.

Exposition is the part in a story where you say things to the reader. Sometimes you want to tell the reader about the past, like history. But sometimes, you should show things to the reader. For example, in a movie, one character tells another about the past. This is called exposition. In a story, the writer does the telling.

Too much exposition can be bad. You can tell the reader many things, or give lots of details. But this can bore the reader. The reader can get confused or even stop reading.

A good example: If you read a story where the heroine met her beloved, got married, and her husband died, you expect to know more about him. You want to see how he loved her, and how she loved him back. You want to feel their love and care. You want to know what made them special. This is called showing. It makes the reader feel more connected to the story.

As a writer, you must show, not just tell. It is hard to resist telling too much. But you must try. You must give the reader enough details to understand the story, but not too much. You must show, not just tell.

I saw two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was live on NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. The main story was about a man named Shad Hostettler in Ashley, Ohio. He stabbed his wife. The news showed his picture. They did not say her name. They said he stabbed her many times and was arrested. They spent about two minutes on this story. I think this was enough time.

The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. An 18-year-old man named Travis Buyers was shot and badly injured. No one was arrested. The SWAT team was looking for the shooter. This story seemed short. I think this might be because Travis is black. Sometimes, the news does not give much attention to crimes involving black people. But when a white person is involved, the news pays more attention.

The next story was about a hole from a bullet found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was from a rifle. They think the bullet might have come from a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered five thousand dollars for information leading to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about rain and thunderstorms. They said it would be in the mid to low eighties on Saturday. They also had a story about a robbery at a store on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He was wearing a hoodie and was about six feet tall and weighed about 150 pounds. They spent a lot of time talking about his race.

The last story was about a man named Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin in Texas. He was sent to prison for 25 years for selling a lot of drugs to Ohio from Texas. They said 25 years is 300 months. I don't know why they said that. They also said he was Hispanic, but that was not important to the story.

Brothers have a strong, special bond. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other better than others. They see themselves in their brother. A brother's true nature shows when problems are big. Understanding these feelings is hard. One must look into a brother's eyes to see their real self. Actions and their results show a person's true nature. In "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers explore this theme. The book describes vivid, beautiful places. They go on a hard journey. Broken dreams, harsh pride, and only one brother lives at the end. The main character, Doodle, and his brother show this theme. The narrator's thoughts show Doodle's feelings and how the world looks to him. These thoughts greatly affect his actions. The main character's actions show his main feeling: pride. He wants to teach his brother skills. He dreams of playing with him. But Doodle is very sick. He can't do these things. The main character is angry. He thinks of harming Doodle. But he loves his brother. A small smile from Doodle makes him feel hope. He doesn't really want to hurt Doodle. In his heart, he loves his brother.

The human brain is a complex, creative machine. As technology changed, so did the ways we describe the brain. First, it was like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, a book, and now a computer. When you learn about the brain, remember: these comparisons are not perfect and can lead to wrong ideas.

Information processing starts with input from our senses. These senses turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, or light into electrical signals. The brain's algorithms turn this sensory information into something usable. There is bottom-up processing, where the brain sorts simple information like color and shape. It also does top-down processing, using earlier decisions to speed up recognition.

After some processing, an attention filter decides what is important. A healthy brain ignores most things, but notices important things like our name in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention changes how we see the results.

To process information, the brain must store it. There are types of memory: sensory, working, and long-term. Information is first stored, then maintained. Working memory lasts about 20 seconds. Long-term memory might be stored in protein structures.

Many models show how knowledge is organized in the brain. Some are based on human memory, computer science, or how the brain works. The semantic network model says there are nodes for concepts, linked based on their relatedness. For example, "chair" might be linked to "table" and "wooden."

Aldous Huxley criticizes both technology and capitalism in Brave New World. He creates a society where people value community more than individuals. They are taught to seek happiness all the time from birth. They are like pieces in a big game controlled by the World Controller. This book shows fears about how these systems develop. Words like "homogeny" and "reification" show this. Capitalism is criticized using a Marxist idea called "false consciousness." People don't understand true relations between classes. They only think about their own gain. They are controlled by the World Controller. Lower classes, like Deltas or Gammas, don't have their own will. They want to spend and consume. This is manipulated. Few Alphas or Betas, like Bernard, do more than accept their place. Social classes interact in ways that show the control of capitalism. People in Brave New World don't have deep relationships. They talk about physical appearance, not feelings. This shows how technology and capitalism take away free will and expression. Each class is happy with their place in society. This is like Marx's idea of the proletariat. They keep consuming and obeying.

I have lived at University Park for 2.5 years, or 4.5 semesters. Many students, including me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls dorm, far from the center. It took 25 minutes to walk to Willard building. Weather made it worse. An old student told me that East Halls were once far from school, but now there are sports fields and new buildings. As campus grows, getting from place to place gets harder. The best solution is a bike. But bikes alone won't fix the problem. Students must ride them, and the campus must be made for them.

A friend of mine started riding again after years. He said, "Bikes are great. It's the only way to get around." Bikes are good for health and travel. They can go 30 miles with just oatmeal and some exercise. I live off campus. A bike is a good choice. It helps me get to Thomas building in 5 minutes, not 25. The road to Thomas is not easy, but a bike is better than walking. Walking would take 30-40 minutes each day. That's 2.5 hours weekly. It's more time than I can spare.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively.
